review.reviewBody: These are great gloves for skiing, perfect for keeping out snow and the cold. I don’t recall having issues with cold in the 3 years that i’ve skied with them but I don’t run cold to begin with. The extra finger gives you so much more control than a normal mitten. Would recommend this glove for skiing and anything outside.

review.reviewBody: First time using these gloves on my bike commute, between 25-28 degrees F (no wind, sunny) I was truly shocked that 10 minutes into the ride my index fingers and thumbs were numb. I ignored other reviewers claiming similar problems. With my old swix gore-tex mittens this would never happen at these temperatures. No doubt that Hestra makes fine crafted gloves, but if you are looking for warmth I would look elsewhere or perhaps try a layering system. Obviously I have not put these through the wringer, grateful that backcountry will exchange for another solution. Similar to others, at this price point, I cannot justify having cold fingers on a 27 degree day after 10-15 minutes of exposure.

review.reviewBody: I’ve had a chance to test these hiking shoes on the rocks and roots in Hawaii. They are comfortable and cool the best feature is the fact that you can’t feel the grave and rocks poking into the bottom of your foot. Construction quality is outstanding. review.itemreviewed: Talus AT Low UltraDry Hiking Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: Start with the good. Great looking shoe. Seems very sturdy leather construction. As others have mentioned in reviews the fault of these shoes is in the tongue. The underside is made up of 2 pieces of material and there is a big seam that hits right on the top of the foot; this is pushed down even more as the laces fall on top of it all. This makes the shoe very uncomfortable and even cuts circulation off in the feet. So it makes them a return.

review.itemreviewed: Talus AT Low UltraDry Hiking Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I've been wearing Vasque hiking shoes and boots for years. Specifically the Talus boot and the Mantra hiking shoe. Great products. Very comfortable. Unfortunately, I had to return the Talus At Low. They fit well except the shoe tongue "presses" into the tops of my feet causing discomfort and soreness. The underside of the tongue has a somewhat stiff/bulky sewn seam that connects two different types of fabrics. The seam  "presses" into the tops of my feet. On my other Vasque boots and shoes, the fabric on the underside of the tongue is a single continuous piece with no seams. Much better for comfort. What also bums me out is that Vasque has been my go-to shoe and now I will have to find a different manufacturer. Also bring back the Mantra 2.0.
review.name: Disappointing
comment: Thank you for your review. I'm sorry to hear that this style didn't work out for you.

Some airports have square tile floors be prepared to hit every groove in every tile and listen to it as you walk almost a mile to your gate. Good luck I've found that having my headphones on blast help...

review.reviewBody: I'm 6'3" with a chest of about 43". According to the size guide, I should be a large. Thankfully I was able to try on a large at a local shop (they didn't have any other sizes) and I realized that it was already going to be way too big i.e., was very loose with the straps tightened all the way; I could take it off like a t-shirt. I bought a medium and I find that it too is too loose: straps are tightened nearly all the way. Definitely a downgrade from my old and tore-up Duro 1.5 that had M/L sizing, adjustable straps on the side (something that would make the new pack much better) and I am surprised by the lack of magnet for the hydration hose. All and in all, it's too loose, moves too much, gets looser as you use up the water, and the lack of magnet makes me really wonder what the designers thought the hydration hose was going to do while running.

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] My kids really like these, nice and warm and were a great price
review.name: Great kids glove

review.reviewBody: My 9 year old daughter tends to prefer gloves over mittens so we decided to snag a pair of these for her to try out. For reference she got a Medium and her palm measures just under 3" across the widest part. She's used them for general snow play, sledding, and skiing in temperatures ranging from low teens to mid 30s F. She says they are really soft inside, fit well, and keep her hands dry even in wet snow, but her fingers get cold quicker than other brands. Perhaps a touch more insulations is needed in the fingers. The "Nectar" color is similar to a Coral shade of pink. The over sleeve portion does well to keep the snow out and the wrist strap keeps them snugly on her hands. They also have a softer portion on the thumbs for wiping snot which is a nice touch I wish my Lander mittens had. From a parent's perspective, the quality is everything we have come to expect from 686.
review.name: Nice, well-made gloves, but could use some more insulation in the fingers.

review.reviewBody:
I absolutely love Beyond Yoga! Everything I’ve purchased from here is so soft and fits perfectly.

Recently, I bought three pairs of leggings, intending to keep only one, but I couldn’t decide which to return—they all fit so well that I ended up keeping all three! I got size small in each pair, and they fit perfectly.

I’ve tried other brands, like Gymshark and Lululemon, but Beyond Yoga stands out. With Gymshark, I returned everything because their leggings kept rolling down at the waist and the sizing was inconsistent. I also considered Lululemon, but I was hesitant due to sizing issues—I’m sometimes a size 4 and sometimes a size 6 in their leggings, which made it hard to choose.

Beyond Yoga is now my go-to brand for leggings. Highly recommend!

 Once they were on they were fine so I thought it would just be a matter of inconvenience but when I wore them on a 4 hour ride home from vacation they hurt my feet, I guess from my feet swelling while sitting so I am so disappointed because I so love Vans but can't wear them for walking since they have low support. I thought these would work perfectly.
review.name: Too constricting

review.reviewBody: I own 28 pairs of vans and these are one of my least favorite designs. They seem like a shoe you would find in the dollar store... how ever I recently got some of the vr3 ultrarange and I highly recommend those
review.name: Cheap design

review.reviewBody: Received a poorly made pair of shoes. Very disappointing.
review.name: Poor quality

review.reviewBody: Like others have said, they are narrow and the overall volume seemed small. I needed to go up a full size! So now they are a little long, but not crazy. I was also hoping to swap out a the foot bed, but they're not removable. I'm happy with them now that I have the right size.
review.name: Size up

review.reviewBody: Found these at Motosport for a great price while searching online. Great communication from seller, arrived quickly! We found they seemed to be a half size smaller. Such a good deal, I gave them to my grandson, and ordered another larger  pair for my son's birthday gift!
review.name: Vans Ultrarange Shoes

review.reviewBody: I love these shoes and the flexibility my feet have in them. They are lightweight, and comfortable. I am really hard on my shoes, so I can get about 8-12 months out of them. Zero complaints.
review.name: Amazing shoes. This is my 10th pair

review.reviewBody: As stated in the other reviews, the toe section is too narrow and sizing is off. Ive worn vans my whole life, and the same size always fits without worry. This is on me cause i didnt read the other reviews just assuming these fit like my others.
review.name: Too narrow

review.reviewBody: I've been wearing vans for years and always size 12, never had to think about it. These shoes would probably be great if you have narrow feet. I don't have a really wide foot (if I did I'd buy a wide shoe) and literally EVERY other pair of vans that I've ever owned fit in size a 12. Except these. I sent them back for a refund. Unfortunately with backcountry.com you have to pay for return shipping. So this whole thing actually cost me money...  I would recommend trying then on at a actual store so your don't come out losing money like I did!
review.name: As others have said. They run small.

review.reviewBody: Wore these for a few weeks now. Love these shoes. Very lightweight and cool. Comfort is def there. Never had a pair.of vans before but def a fan! They are true to size also.
review.name: Great shoes!!!

review.reviewBody: My entire family now has a pair of Smith I/O MAGs. For those of us who've used them for a few years, they are still as good as new. We each had to experiment with the various sizes/fits in order to ensure no fogging while in use, but this was easy to do. The magnetic connection makes popping in the desired lens so effortless; the only thing I wish was slightly better was the release mechanism. There is a tab that must be pushed a bit in order for the lens to be released, and I always worry I'm about to break it (it's a hard plastic) - but we haven't damaged any yet. Clearly, it's better made than I could tell. Overall, a great product. I only wish it was possible to mix/match the day/storm lenses upon purchase. An extra set lens (storm) came with each goggle purchase, but I wasn't able to select the hue.
review.name: Great Googles

review.reviewBody: Great quality product (lenses and frame) and very easy to change lenses.

review.reviewBody: They kept me warm! I’m new to skiing but my bf and his family are pros so I went with what they told me are good and I don’t have any regrets I was warm and safe the two days we went skiing. There was a sunny and a cloudy days and it was easy to snap in the different lenses for the conditions. I also like that they match my other gear! Overall I would get them again if I needed to.
review.name: They kept me warm! I’m

review.reviewBody: The snap out and in lens are amazing. I like the flexibility of changing lens for the conditions. Excellent fit with my Smith helmet.

review.reviewBody: They seem to work very well. I haven't worn the original lens yet, only the lighter extra lens that was provided - which was awesome. They fit with my helmet perfectly (not a Smith) and fit my smaller face much better than previous goggles I've owned. The clip on the strap is interesting - I've never had one like that before. I was nervous it would fall off when adjusting but it never did.

review.reviewBody: It is a great size and room for short work trips. Material feels solid. I have been using more back pack styles but with this, I am liking the sling style bags too.

review.reviewBody: Bought it a few weeks ago and currently travelling and remote working in Europe. This bag takes in my laptop, my second portable screen, all the adaptors and cables, note books, books e-reader and so on. Using it as a personal item in the plane, so depending on the plane companies I have to empty it a little, but no issue with Air Canada. Overall great quality, and being able to put it as a bag on your back is great. But as some mentionned, some "grip" or "cushion" are missing on the shoulder strap and makes for an easy slide if you have other bags with you, so carefull with that. But this is a great bag, happy that I got it on discount though... would never have bought it full price...

review.reviewBody: Definitely like the bag. Read the reviews talking about the shoulder strap and agree it could use some work. As for pockets, they hold what I need. Even the expansion has come in handy. The shoulder strap is the only reason it didn’t get the 5 stars.

review.reviewBody: I bought the 3 Way expandable 18 as a briefcase that is small enough to pack on the engine but fit a work computer, tablet, and PT clothes. I have yet to use the expandable feature. Plenty of storage, and I’m happy I didn’t opt for the larger size.

review.reviewBody: This is a really nice, quality bag. I just wish I’d had ordered the larger version. This one is a bit on the small side.
review.name: Great Quality, just a little small

review.reviewBody: Only just bought this so time will tell how it holds up but I’m confident it will last me a long time. I am on the go with my work computer/ipad/notepad 5 days a week and needed something slightly larger without being obnoxiously huge…this fit the bill in terms of size perfectly. The zippers are a bit stiff/difficult to open but I am sure with time and exercise they’ll loosen up. Overall I definitely recommend, it feels very well made, looks great and the pockets/storage is well thought out.
review.name: Just the size I needed

review.reviewBody: Excellent quality. Bag is perfectly proportioned, great design, high quality.
review.name: Sturdy construction

review.reviewBody: This bag is awesome; the compartment space is perfect and easy to keep organized. The right point of storage for smaller items without your stuff getting lost. clean , well-made, simple, and robust. Nuff said.
review.name: Killer work & travel bag

review.reviewBody: I saw some coworkers in BC Wildfire with this laptop bag and decided to purchase one for myself. I am so far very pleased with the bag! All the stuff that was normally yard-saled across the front seat of my truck I can now organize in one compact space. Laptop, maps, GPS, Kestrel, notebooks, pens, keys, wallets, phones, radios, chargers, etc. all have a spot. The quality and durability is what I expect from Mystery Ranch, and while I understand the complaints others have about the shoulder strap, it doesn't bother me as I'm not traveling long distances with the bag on my shoulder.
review.name: So far, so great!

review.reviewBody: only have taken it for a few trips but it has become my favorite. I like the size and plenty  pockets for organization.

review.reviewBody: I was fed up with the women’s zero g not coming in a higher flex so, bought the men’s tour pro. The shell is the same size, no volume difference, and the flex is 130. Ended up doing several corn tours and had a surprise pow day, even tried them in bounds one day. My conclusion: great boot! It is the burly but light weight boot of my dreams. I would use this for the resort, but for the bc it is outstanding. *I would rather have a bit more weight for a premium down hill, my opinion. And the boot doesn’t really weigh much at all, relative to others of its class. My only concern is that the liner my pack out quick like my last pair of zero g’s but we shall see…Otherwise I’d say, Técnica needs to make women’s boots with more flex! A woman who wears a 26.5 ski boot is not a small woman! We want a woman’s boot with more flex got it! Ok enough ranting…overall this is the best bc ski boot I’ve ever owned.
review.name: Great Burly Touring Boot

review.reviewBody:
Amazing boot. Very good articulation and reasonable weight for the uphill. Best downhill performance of any boot I’ve been in over the past 20 years of backcountry.  You can find lighter boots for the uphill, but there is nothing that beats 4 buckle downhill performance. Good feedback from the ski, and the flex works well for me. Length is true to size, and while it may be a narrow last, overall volume is on the mid range side of things (I’ve added a couple footbed shims to take up some volume). Sure transitions take a bit longer with 4 buckles but who cares - unless you’re racing, in which case you’re not looking at this boot anyhow.
It is difficult to get your foot into - the combination of rigid shell overlaps and the ankle features built into the liner combine to make it a bit of a struggle at the trailhead. But use a boot horn and all is good.  But the same items that make it difficult to put on, make it a great boot by grabbing your foot on both the up and down.
review.name: Great uphill and downhill

review.reviewBody: Great boot for b/c or lift service. Picked up my second pair after first pair were breaking down. I would have rated it at a 5 if power strap hook was facing down. My only complaint with the 2nd pair is the power strap buckle. For some unknown reason the hook opening is facing up so the strap falls out when skinning. Why is this a problem? It catches on hobblebush when it hangs down after coming unhooked. I don't like the top two buckles or power strap tight when in climbing mode. If you don't know what hobblebush is coming ski in the woods on the east coast.
review.name: Second pair of W Zero G

review.reviewBody:
Extremly well engineered touring boot, which
- offers low weight and mobility for uphills
- is a (little) hard to get in and out of
- can almost match downhill performance of some alpine boots
- fits even my foot (narrow heel and wider forefoot with just heat fitting)

Overall its a 50/50 boot, if you want to go for big drops and fast freeride lines this could be a bit to "spongy" otherwise this will serve any downhill purpose. Cannot judge durability yet as I purchased mine only 1y ago. Fits great with my setup (Petzl Irvis Crampons, ATK R12 on Camox Freebirds). Overall very happy that I got it despite beeing skeptical bc of the "narrow" last.
review.name: Outstanding Touring Boot

review.reviewBody:
As a former self-proclaimed "free-tourer", I got tired of having heavy boots with poor range of motion. These boots are a breath of fresh air. Light enough to not fatigue you on bigger days, but burley enough to handle steep lines. I cannot understate the difference that a proper walk mode and big range of motion makes in efficiency going uphill. Total game changer. 

For reference I toured in the Lange XT3's for many years, which shined in downhill performance. the Zero G Tour Pro has a comparable downhill performance with a significantly better uphill performance. I've never been on a line in these boots where I craved a stiffer boot. The power strap and classic 4-buckle design does an excellent job locking down your foot and not allowing you to flex too far through the boot when you ski it aggressively.  

There is a reason you see so many of these on the skinner, they are some of the best boots I've ever been in and I don't plan on looking for a new boot any time soon.
review.name: Unmatched Performance

review.reviewBody: I am 6 ft tall (190 lbs) and wear a tight 27.5. I use these all across eastern Canada backcountry skiing. Very light considering that it is fully adjustable, comfortable for the climb and a very solid boot for skiing. Definitely my go to. Love these boots!
review.name: My go to for great adventure

review.reviewBody: I have them for two years and I am really satisfied. They are comfortable and light. A little more liner support would be welcome when going down. It's a good compromise between lightness and downhill capabilities
review.name: Great boots!

review.reviewBody:
These boots are light, have excellent grip, and are perfect for going uphill. Once set to skiing position they make you really enjoy any descent at high speeds, whether off or on pist, due to their stiffness.
Moreover, the customer service is simply the best that you can get! I contacted the customer service twice in the last two years (I really like Tecnica products I must say) and they always replied immediately and provided me with the solution to my problems!
review.name: Great boots!

Thank you.

review.name: Best fitting helmet ever

review.reviewBody: As an Asian, I have never found helmets that fit until I found Troy Lee Designs. My first helmet was a full-face and it fit really well. Same goes for this helmet. The magnetic chin strap buckle is easy to use.
review.name: Great for a difficult head

review.reviewBody:
Got this as a replacement helmet after a crash, and I am very happy with it. As someone who is between a medium and large helmet the M/L is perfect, I really like that it is lower profile than my old L Smith helmet while providing more coverage. I was a bit worried because other reviewers complained about their riding glasses not fitting comfortably but I have had none of those issues. In fact this is the most comfortable helmet I've ever worn including how the glasses stems sit, there is ample room while the helmet still provides great temple coverage.

Next time I replace a helmet I will be coming back to the A3.
review.name: Great half shell

review.reviewBody:
This helmet is amazing.  It fits so well and is so comfortable.  It has MIPS.  It has the magnetic strap.  
It has an adjustable visor. All not too unusual.  

Then you get to the liner.  The front of the helmet has like a gasket, a squeegee like silicone or rubber part that sits against your forehead.  
In all my years of sweating profusely I have never found anything that actually prevents sweat getting into my eyes.   Until now.  
This doohickey actually works.  I would say it prevents about 80% of my shower-like, profuse sweat from getting into my face.   It’s a game-changer.
review.name: Best helmet for heavy/extreme sweating.

review.reviewBody:
This is the best helmet I have ever worn. It is comfortable, cool, highly adjustable, easy to rinse after a ride, and based on reviews, very protect that that whole brain thing. I really like that way it channels forehead sweat away from my face. 

Oh, and it is great looking. This is the only helmet for which I got paid a compliment by another rider. Obviously a case of helmet envy.
review.name: Best Helmet I Ever Used

review.reviewBody: bought for my mountain bike, fits well very comfortable (XL)

review.reviewBody:
I have been riding in this helmet for a few weeks, solid. I was a bit uncomfortable spending over $200 on a trail lid, as anything i've bought in the past was about 150 max. A friend of mine that knows product well, swore i'd love the helmet.
I do.
It is so comfortable and packed with features that made me have zero buyers remorse. The ability to refine the fit as well simply with the adjuster, but if you want to go beyond and tune the comfort liner was a cool option. 
It looks great, feels incredible, vents well, looks like a expensive piece of kit.
A+ job from these people. I am a 56cm and the M/L fits me like a glove with about 1/3rd to almost half of the retention dial turned in.
review.name: really comfortable

review.reviewBody: I tried these on at home and immediately knew I had to return them. The heel "catch" is way too low and doesn't hold your heel in place. Instead of catching up near the Achilles, it catches midway down the heel. Felt like a loose fitting house slipper. My old Giro Privateers fit much better with absolutely no heel slip. Went with these because I thought they would hike a bit better on rocky trails than an XC oriented shoe, but with this amount of heel slip there's just no way these will hike well.
review.name: Decent shoe, but loads of heel slip

review.reviewBody: I bought these to replace my tired Specialized Rime Expert shoes. I didn't want a shoe that screamed XC and I didn't want a shoe that looked like an orthopedic skate shoe either. These not only fit that bill, but they matched the colors of my V1 Ibis Ripmo in the black and olive perfectly, not to mention my WTB tanwalls with the gum outsole. With that color combo, I couldn't really see any alternative! I ended up ordering a size 43 instead of my normal 44 based on reviews that it fit large and I kind of regret it. The shoes fit my rather narrow size 10 feet, but the toe box is just a hair too small. It doesn't ever bother me on the bike, but I know that they could fit better. The Boa dial can also be a bit finicky to release, but I'm never in a race to take them off. Other than those issues, the shoes are fantastic. The gum-colored outsoles are grippy enough for short hike-a-bike sections while still feeling durable. They also feel like the offer a decent amount of protection from rock strikes. I'm really glad a took a shot on these and it always makes me smile when I see how well they match my ride. I know that's a silly reason to like a pair of shoes...but I don't care. I'd buy them again if I had to.
review.name: I love them, but they're not perfect

review.reviewBody: Typical fit for Giro shoes with the exception with some extra, much appreciated (for me at least), room in the toe box. I?ve had some heel slippage on hike-a-bikes but in my experience that is to be expected in a bike specific shoe. Tread has good grip. One of those shoes I may just buy an extra pair in fear of Giro discontinuing them.
review.name: Wiggle Room

review.reviewBody: 4 months review on these guys. I liked them most of the time. Pretty stiff, heel comes out when hike a biking. But I am more of an enduro oriented guy and I feel like the shoe was too flexy torsionally and made me feel unstable on the bike. I think this shoe is not made for too aggressive of riding. I would appreciate more stiffness, I am looking to get the Kestrel Boa now and will update a comparison to those. Overall though, not a bad shoe and pretty durable so far, just want more.
review.name: Comfortable, but flexy

review.reviewBody:
I would echo all of the other reviews, except on the point of sizing.  First time in a Giro shoe, so cant speak to sizing across the brand.  I wear 10.5-11 in street shoes.  I have been wearing a 10.5 in Freerider Pros and 44 in Specialized. Ordered the 43 based on reviews (Would have gone with a 43.5 if available, was skeptical ordering the 43) and it ultimately was too tight for me?both in overall length and the arch.  Went with the 44s and perfect for me.  Toe box is relatively wide for a cycling shoe?a plus. 
Great shoe.

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody:
I’ve. Been using his rack for 7 years and it’s still works great, it’s very cumbersome and heavy so it takes 2 people to guide it in the receiver, but once you do it’s there for the season, which is April -October here in New England.
I love how I can still have access to the trunk by swinging it out, with or without bikes loaded on it.

It’s very sturdy and comes with excellent straps to hold the bike, they easily pop in,.
 We are looking to get fat tire bikes so we will defintelt go with the Thule brand as it’s trusted cabs well made.
review.name: Love my Thule swing out bike rack

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody:
I have had this bike rack for a year now and have used it to carry 1-4 bikes over many many miles on the road. This has been one of the most disappointing products Thule has made due to how much potential it has and how difficult it is to live with on a day to day basis. I had high expectations that I would be able to keep the rack on day to day and carry bikes easily. Both expectations were not met. Two major flaws with the design doom it from the start. The strap system when carrying bikes and the locking system of the arms. The straps system is a disaster and there isn't any way around it. I have yet to find a way to release the straps without using two hands, ton of pain to my fingers and a ton of time. I've worked on a single trap for 3 minutes before I was able to release it. I've read and reread the instructions to see if there is something I'm doing wrong. Nope. The plastic straps just don't let you depress the release mechanisms. I can't even imagine doing this in cold weather. The second flaw is that the swing arm locks with a screw that is accessed down near the bottom between the hitch and the rack. this means every time you want to swing the rack out you got to get down and unscrew the swing arms. This can take a while if the rack is loaded with bikes. Every other mechanism on this rack is a simple latch placee in a easily accessible and ergonomic position. For what it's worth the plastic alignment piece also broke within the first 2 months. 

I will give credit where it is due and say there are no sagging issues with the swing arm and the locking cable is a nice touch. I also haven't had a bike fall off either. 1 Star there i guess. 

Buyer beware. This product is hard to live with day to day with bikes, it's even harder to use when putting bikes on the rack. For the price I was expecting much better and regret buying this product.
review.name: Poor execution to a great concept
comment:
Thank you for sharing your feedback on Thule Apex XT. I am sorry to hear this bike rack did not meet your expectations. A Thule representative ahs reached out to see if we can assist with any troubleshooting. 
The ratcheting straps on this rack do generally require two hands to operate. This is a change from previous versions, but was made in favor of increased durability and a greater degree of adjustment to better fit bike frames. Issues with releasing the straps is sometimes due to over-tightening, which can cause the ratchet teeth to bind. Tighten the strap so it just fits over the bike frame, rather than trying to get an extra click or two out of the mechanism for easy releases. 
Likewise, the vehicle and bike combination used with this bike rack may make it difficult to reach the swing release knob. This is an unfortunate necessity to ensure the swing mechanism is secure while fully loaded for travel.

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody:
This is a solid rack that once tightened in the hitch doesn't move, rattle or squeak.
The rachets take a bit of breaking in but once used are tight and the bikes don't move.
Use the strap for the tires. A huge convenience.
The rack weighs a little bit but the compact nature when folded makes it easy to move around or on and off the hitch mount.  Way less weight than a 4 bike bottom tray carrier and the Apex minimally obscures the rear camera.  Not a huge deal you can still use the rear camera feature of the vehicle, unlike some other racks.
Overall I'm very satisfied with the Apex rack.
review.name: Solid bike rack!

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody: I bought this a few months ago and used multiple times. I have a Infinity QX80 and when I extend the arm with the bikes on I can't open the trunk. I guess this product is designed more for small and medium SUV not for a big one. But so far I'm happy with this product.
review.name: Good product

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody: Bike rack looks stable. I had an earlier version of the same thing and it would open fairly easily. The new one is very hard to swing out. Not sure how to make it smoother. Also, once you fully swing the rack out to open the liftgate, the swing rack locks into place. Trying to figure out how to unlock it.
review.name: Very Stiff and hard to open.

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody:
We wanted to love this rack, but there's just too much to dislike about it.

It's a pain to have to squoosh between the bikes and the car to unscrew the locking mechanism every time you need to swing the bikes out to open the tailgate. Surely some sort of locking quick release like on other brands could have been designed. 

You're also advised to unlock the hitxh lock and tighten the knob every couple of hundred km. Does not inspire confidence.

The biggest pain is that the tailpiece sticks out so far from the hitch receiver, that you will keep grinding the back end of the rack into the pavement every time you go up or down a steep driveway entrance, unless your receiver is particularly high. On our Forester, which is quite high, we were forced to install a hitch lifter in the middle of a 10,000 mile road trip after numerous bashes. 

So we used it for the one trip, and are now going to sell it. Great ideas, very poor execution.
review.name: Could have been so much better
comment:
Thank you for sharing your thoughts on Thule Apex XT Swing. I understand that some of the features can create inconvenient situations in some circumstances. The mechanics of the rack system are designed to ensure a safe connection between the swing components, the bike rack and the vehicle. While releasing the swing pin requires moving around the bikes, this is the optimal position for a secure connection. Likewise, the extension from the rear of the vehicle is required to ensure Thule Apex XT Swing can adequately clear most rear bumpers and pivot far enough for tailgate access.
Thule always recommends checking hitch-mounted bike rack connection periodically throughout long trips as a safety precaution. While this is rarely actually needed, it is generally good practice to check the connection throughout a trip, even just checking that the bike rack is still secure to the hitch when stopping for gas.

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody: This bike rack is amazing! Very easy to mount/unmount, stabilizes bikes and looks great too. The added feature of the swing allows is so convenient to be able to access the trunk.
review.name: Worth every penny!

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody: Easy to install and use right out of the box.  Very sturdy.  First major trip was 4 bikes (2 adults, 2 kids) and no issues.  My old hitch rack (from ~90's) would bounce and seemed unsteady.  Not the case with the new Apex....rack seemed very stout.  The swing feature was very helpful for still accessing the bed of my 2019 Tundra.
review.name: Repeat Thule customer

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody: Great product but the manual is lacking important details, like instructing you to use the 'blank' key to install the lock bolt into the bike rack.  There is a major lack of copy in the manual and just a little direction would have made the entire installation process smoother.
review.name: Manual Lacking Instructions
comment:
Thank you for sharing your feedback. 
I understand your frustration with the format of Thule's user manuals. They are printed with less text than may be seen in other products because they are designed to be read in the many different languages used in the regions Thule products are sold across the world. Reducing text reduces the need for additional translations and possible errors of technical information, as well as the paper waste generated from printed manuals.

review.itemreviewed: Apex XT Swing Away Bike Rack - 4 Bike
review.reviewBody: Straight forward installation, sturdy with quality built even fully loaded.
review.name: Love this rack!

review.reviewBody:
Got this for my wife, and she loved how warm it was and the "Indigo Night" color.  She said she could feel the warmth the instant she tried it on.

That said, it has the most bizarre fit of any fine garment I've ever seen, and she understandably could not deal with that.  The upper back sides project 2-3" out from her outer shoulder blades starting at her outermost shoulders and extending down to about mid-back on each side.

It looks as if she has two machete blades sticking out from the sides of her upper back.  She does have petite shoulders/arms, but she has never had any similar problem with the many brands of other fleeces she owns (her favorite outerwear).
Still even for a woman with broad/more muscular shoulders, it's hard to imagine that they wouldn't the same problem...just less of it probably.

So, very weird fit of shoulder/back area.  Normal fit for rest of it.
5 for warmth and looks, 1 for fit, and an average of 3 for rating.
review.name: Big Shoulders

True to size, I am 5' 5'' and 130 lb, size M is good for me to wear two layers under the jacket.

review.reviewBody: I would give it a 3.5 of 5 starts. Love the ‘no slosh’ bladders and overall snug fit and various pockets / compartments to carry things. Bladders hold enough fluid for about a 10m run. Vest is overall a great design and I would recommend it to others. Some improvements: sizing chart is off. I have a 40” chest. Per the dimension guidance (foto #2) I ordered a Medium. However, the actual vest is very tight causing the bladders to be way off to the side (foto #1) making them hard to reach when running - I need to take both hands and pull the bladder towards my mouth to drink. Secondly, it’s pretty hard to get the elastic string inside the clasp. The clasp mouth should either be slightly wider, or have more of an angled bevel to help guide the string to its mouth. It takes about 3-4 tries to get the string inside the claps. Again, I do like the vest, but think these corrections would help.

review.reviewBody: I have the Rodvault 2 and it definitely serves its purpose and provides the convenience that I expected. The issue I have with the rodvault is the build quality from Thule is not up to par with other Thule products, which tend to be over engineered and bombproof. The mounting brackets to the vehicle are the worst parts of this rack, they are a single bolt into all plastic pieces, including the bar contact surfaces. There is no grip on the bars so I have to loosen and readjust as the rack twists every so often from highway winds. There are no lock cores for the mounts and even if you do lock them with a pad lock through the provided hole, the mounts are plastic and anyone could walk up and break the entire rack off with ease. The rest of the rack is ok enough but does seem like it should cost about half of what it does. The tubes and reel box have no padding so make sure that you use a neoprene reel pouch to protect your reels from damage. The rubber magnetic strap does nothing so disregard that piece and the tubes’ fore and aft pieces are twisted when assembled. The lock core is not your typical Thule core, which is odd so you cannot change the core to match the rest of your rack keys. Overall, it’s a simple product that serves its purpose and keeps you rigged up when on the move but has much to be desired. There are other rod holders on the market that cost slightly more which seem to have the quality that this one lacks. When I replace this rack, I certainly will be upgrading to a different brand. Hopefully, until then, my rodvault doesn’t get stolen.
review.name: Great concept but lacks the expected Thule quality

review.reviewBody:
The RodVault does what is says and what it needs to do. The convenience of being able to get to your fishing spot fully rigged and ready to cast is fantastic. I'll be giving the rod vault plenty of use. 

Assembly went smoothly though the instructions lacked any images and left a bit of ambiguity in the assembly process.

My disappointment with the product comes from an overall lower quality than what I have come to expect from Thule. The front section of the rod tubes are out of alignment and results in a slight twist down the length of the RodVault. The Reel enclosure doesn't have any padding or protection which seems like miss. Importantly, the locking mechanism uses a different lock core and key from the rest of the Thule product line. Having to keep another key close at hand is a disappointment. Additionally, the mounting clamp does not accept locking cores and lacks the finesse of the rest of the Thule line. I'm looking forward to a ton of adventures with the Rod Vault on the car but would have liked to see the usual attention to detail that I've come to expect.
review.name: Functional but not normal Thule quality

review.reviewBody: I just installed this on my Jeep Patriot and have used it a few times. It was easy enough to install and does a great job of keeping my rods safe & secure. Being able to show up to the river with my rods already rigged makes a huge difference.
review.name: Great rod tube!

review.reviewBody: I bought two of these- one for my car and one for the pickup. The one on the car is fine, but for those of you that leave the pavement, beware. I had to check the mounts constantly, tightening the bolt that clamps the tubes to the mount. I forgot to check it for a couple of trips on rough roads, and one of the clamps rattled right off! Thankfully I had some straps that I used to secure the missing mount for the return trip. Also the design of this mount/tube clamp means that to tighten the clamps, you have to undo two other bolts to access the clamp bolt. So unfortunately, it is more labor intensive than just grabbing a wrench and doing a few turns, not to mention the risk of your rods jumping free!
review.name: Can't handle off-pavement travel
comment:
Thank you for sharing your feedback on the Thule RodVault 2. I am sorry to hear about the damage to the system. 
Thule products are tested under most standard road driving conditions, but are not generally tested to certification standards for off-road use. Because they have not been certified for these conditions, Thule cannot guarantee the safe operation of the products for such driving. 
Thule is working to expand its product testing criteria to include off-road travel. This process will take time to ensure all products are tested and approved for the highest safety ratings possible.

review.reviewBody: While my husband won't be able to use this before spring, he is very excited about it.  A couple of friends have them and he really wanted one.  I can't wait to see it in action.
review.name: Best Christmas give ever!

review.reviewBody: My son gave one to me for Christmas in 2020. I used it a fair amount last season and loved it. The spots I fish require me to load up and move in my truck to access different spots. Plus, when I pull up to the locations my rod is set up and ready to go. Saves tons of time. The way its built provides reasonable security but I will never leave them in a motel parking lot with rods in them. The only complaint I have is the rubber strap with magnets that is a kind of bungee cord used to secure the rods inside does not work well at all and the magnets come off. They can be put back on if you have them. I would buy Thule Vaults again. Very happy with mine.
review.name: Well made product that works great.

review.reviewBody: I just purchased a dual rod holder and found out that my Orvis mid size arbor reels will not fit. I have to tilt the reel to be able to carry one rod. This does me no good as I purchased this to carry 2 rigged fly rods.

comment:
Thank you for sharing your feedback on the Thule RodVault 2. 
The Thule RodVault 2 is compatible with most fly fishing reels up to 4.25" in diameter. The rod tubes themselves have 1.5" of clearance. 
I am sorry the rods and reels you were using did not fit this fly rod carrier. This is a new and evolving product line for Thule, and our product development teams are working hard to make sure subsequent models of the carrier suit as many customer needs as possible.

review.reviewBody: I really wanted to like these and looked forward to getting both the two and four rod models. Sadly they weren’t able to handle the gravel road I lived on. They filled with dust despite being locked closed and punished the rods and reels inside. Maybe these are ok if you don’t leave pavement often. If you do, the damage to equipment isn’t worth the few seconds of time savings rigging.
review.name: Can’t handle a bumpy road
comment:
Thank you for taking the time to reach out and provide your feedback. 

Thule RodVaults are designed to provide optimal protection for your fishing rods. Damage to the rods inside could be caused by installation issues or material defects with the carriers. I reached out directly via email for more information so we can find the cause and resolve this problem!

review.reviewBody:
Clark L. 3/2/2021
Fly fishing here in Idaho with 2 handled Spey rods for Steelhead, fly rods to over 14' may need to be broken down into 2 strung rod parts. review.reviewBody: Look, I put these tubes in for a race, and they were a dream. Very light, and they rode unbelievably, I couldn't believe what a difference they made in the ride. Then a couple rides later I get TWO PINCH FLATS IN THE SAME RIDE 15 miles apart, leaves me with a 2 mile walk of shame. That was just the beginning. I can only use their special patches, right? For TWO MONTHS I look everywhere, nobody has them in stock. TWO MONTHS! So I finally give in last week and buy the Park Tools glueless patches. They actually seem to work pretty well, but I'll never know because as I'm getting everything repaired and ready to ride, my valve literally BLOWS OUT of the plastic (yes, plastic) valve stem. Threads are ruined, won't hold a valve or an extender in the stem. Trash. Waste of money. Don't think I'll waste my time trying to install the other aerothan that I repaired.
review.name: Wow, unreal (in a bad way)

review.reviewBody: I got exactly 1188 miles on the tube mounted in the front wheel. Today the tube went flat after a fast 51mph steep descent where I had to come to a very quick stop because the road ends. I typically air up the pressure to 85psi  in my 25mm R3 tires before every ride. Today I didn't do that and I can only guess how much pressure was in it since it's common for the tire to lose about 10 to 15 psi per day. I hit the disc brakes hard and I felt a bump that felt like a pinch and I rolled about another 40 yards before the tire was completely flat. There was nothing on the road that I could see so it could only be from low pressure and all the weight forward from braking that may have resulted in a pinch flat. I looked at the tube and you can clearly see two little snake bite marks. Schwalbe claims you can patch these but I have read that patches won't stick. If that is true then these tubes would not be worth the asking price. Depending on the hole I can patch a common tube several times and get a lot more miles. I still have 2 more Aerothan tubes so I will continue on and see if the next tube will last until it's time for a new tire. I would like to see a tube last as long as a tire before replacing it. If I could patch it then I could replace it when I install a new tire. This doesn't seem like it's going to be the case. No way to predict what kind of mileage you are going to get from the Aerothan tubes but I'm already at $60 in the same tire when normally I would have only spent $10 to $12 dollars.
review.name: Mixed feeling.

review.reviewBody: I have had great success using the Tubolito tubes, which ride nicely, are very light, are almost freakish in their ability to hold air and never get punctured. Just for kicks I tried these *very* similar tubes on a second, 'back up' bike for commuting and they work exactly the same, but the stem is black and not orange like the Tubolitos. No complaints.
review.name: They work

review.reviewBody:
All I can say is that the legend of precision German engineering is seriously brought into question from quality control and design failures of these tubes.  Never in my 10 years of "serious" cycling have I had a tube fail at the stem.  In this case it happened twice, with the threading on the valve being too weak to even stay in the stem when inflated to 85psi.  

I really wanted to like these tubes. I've used Schwalbe's other products for years and have been pleased with the construction and durability.  

In fairness I did enjoy the ride quality while they lasted (only about 400 miles). But at $35 a pop how many failures every 400 miles would equal a new set of tubeless wheels?  One pair is a decent jersey...or half of a decent pair of bibs (you can decide which half).
review.name: Pass until they work out the flaws.

review.reviewBody: The boot itself seems fine although I've only worn them once.  The laces are horrible. They don't stay tied. The first time I wore them, it was at night. review.reviewBody: The main reason I purchased these was because they are advertised as wide width. Very few options for wide width hiking shoes. I ordered my regular size, 9W. review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Wide - Women's
review.reviewBody: This is my 3rd pair. I wear them everyday - I am a daily walker. They are comfortable, great for wide feet, are just right in all ways. I am happy. My feet and body alignment are happy.

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Wide - Women's
review.reviewBody: Really happy with this choice.  I knew quality would be excellent just with past experience with Merrell but you never know about the fit / feel when you mail order.  Fortunately, these felt great immediately.  I didn't get to "break them in" gently - I threw them on before going out to a forested area with no path going uphill - so lot of dips, sticks, snags, logs, etc.   Gave them a good trial by fire and they felt terrific!   And really attractive too.
review.name: Great purchase from day one!

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Wide - Women's
review.reviewBody: So far so good. As someone with foot problems who nevertheless prefers to be barefoot, shoes in general are tough for me. I find these Merrells quite comfortable. I got the wide width and am glad I did. They have been to France and back with me!

review.reviewBody:
This has become my new favorite tent. It has a few things I wish could be changed (hence the 4 stars rather than 5) but overall this is a fantastic piece of gear. Just came back from using it on a 3-week camping trip through the Canadian Rockies. Tent held up extremely well during big storms (solid rain for hours, wind gusts over 40mph). Zero leaks and the rain fly did a great job of keeping things comfortable inside the tent. The materials were incredibly high quality, including some truly beefy tent poles, a generous number of pre-attached guy lines, a huge ground tarp included, good storage inside.   The tent itself is very spacious and I love the massive vestibule. 

A few downsides:  1) absolutely terrible pitching instructions (why design so many cool features on a tent and then not explain how to set it up properly and use everything?) and 2) the vestibule zippers are near impossible to open from the inside — the zippers immediately get caught on the fabric flaps that cover the zipper (I had to reach *under* the edge of the vestibule with one hand to hold the flap aside and then use my other hand to open the zipper).  It’s a bit tricky to set up by yourself since the rain fly is enormous but it’s hard to call that a flaw since the whole point in buying this tent was to secure a good size shelter for rough weather.
review.name: Almost perfect

review.reviewBody: Can you believe it, a car camping tent for 4 that actually fits 4?! It’s true! Setup is straightforward, I was able to pack it all back up into the sling bag it came with it which was a relief. One of the loops was missing to hold back the porch flap, our only quibble.
review.name: Sensible and Roomy

review.reviewBody: Once used. Very accommodating and impressive quality. Suggest using a secondary ground cloth first under the provided one which will not handle rough ground
review.name: Very pleased

review.reviewBody: really solid tent.  slept 4 just fine.  a bit heavy and unweildy as a back country tent but I took it on a canoeing trip and most of the time it was just in the boat.  But on the portages it was a bit heavy and bulky.  That said, it performed really well in its core job and did repel 2 nights of rain really well while being large enough to actually hold 4 grown people.
review.name: A solid performer.

review.reviewBody: This tent is well designed and well made with high quality materials. It is a great car-camping tent. My wife and I and our two full-sized dogs fit easily in the tent with two EXPED Megamats and two full-sized dog beds. We went through a torrential rain with no problem. Everything stayed dry.
review.name: Great Car-Camping Tent

review.reviewBody: Super roomy tent you can easily stand up and move around. Takes a bit if you are setting up by yourself, but once up, it is great.
review.name: Big, roomy

review.reviewBody: Top quality materials and craftsmanship. Used it for the first time over 4th of July weekend. Just two of us and it was the perfect size for car camping. We were able to fit a queen size blow up bed and have enough room on the sized for our clothes and items. The extra storage in the vestibule is a great addition; we used it for easy reach to car keys, sun screen, and layers. My only complaint is how large the rain cover is when not on the tent. It's a lot of fabric to manage and move around. I also find the air ventilation could be improved. With the rain fly on, it gets a little stuffy until the night time temperatures cool. We were able to use the vestibule during a rain show and it was perfect for our two chairs and a small table between us. I also really liked that the standard setup does not have random guy lines to trip on. All the stakes are near the tent and the front vestibule lines are built into the entrance panels. I never had to worry about tripping on a line during the night.
review.name: Top quality car camping tent. Could use more venting to cool down quicker during, but overall a great car camping tent for a couple.

review.reviewBody: I’m a fan of the tent. It works well. The vestibule entry with gear pockets is great. Easy enough to put up, even if solo.
review.name: Would buy again

review.reviewBody: My wife and I retired our 12 year old Nemo Asashi 4P and were sad to see it go (it had been through a lot!), but excited for something new. We decided on the MH-Bridger 4P because the sleeping space was similar size (although taller) yet added the large vestibule/garage which we knew we would use in inclement weather in the Rockies. Little did we know that we would use the garage on the first night as it began to snow on us as we were making dinner at a campground in the Western Black Hills on Memorial Day weekend. We were so happy to be able to move our camp chairs and cooler inside for a relaxing meal instead of the cab of the truck. Overall, this is a very comfortable and easy to pitch tent. Plenty of interior storage/pockets, including a very small gear loft which is one of only a couple complaints in that it is much too small. The other more serious complaint is that the two zippers for the vestibule canopy get caught on the outside zipper flap WAY too easily, especially when trying to open from the inside. We’re still looking for a workaround but I feel if the zipper weather flaps were wider (or shorter?) that it wouldn’t be as much of an issue. Otherwise it really is a fantastic tent!
review.name: Not perfect but pretty great

review.reviewBody: This seems to be a well-made tent. Luxurious, even. It hasn't been tested yet in strong winds, or several days of rain. It did stand up well to several hours of rain, and stayed dry during a light snowstorm. The build up of snow on the rainfly (a few melting inches) did start to cause dripping on the footprint in the vestibule. But this tent isn't made for snow. Pluses: height, pockets on inside of vestibule and tent, and the generous front vestibule. Negatives: the front door of the rainfly (over the vestibule) is not that easy to deal with, as the zippers are on the sides and there is voluminous fly to deal with. The zippers tend to get caught in the fabric that protects them. Also: Be ready to deal with a very large, unwieldy fly when cleaning/drying (after mud splashes) and breaking down the tent in inclement weather.  This tent is larger than it seems in pics/description. Definitely a base camp type tent.
review.name: Comfortable, Well-Designed Tent

review.itemreviewed: R1 Air Full-Zip Hooded Jacket - Men's

review.name: Favorite piece of mid layer insulation

review.itemreviewed: R1 Air Full-Zip Hooded Jacket - Men's

review.itemreviewed: R1 Air Full-Zip Hooded Jacket - Men's
